The best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already covers `File.*`, `Directory.*`, `Path.*`, etc. No need to write a custom wrapper.

Here's how to adopt it with your project:

### 1. Install packages

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
# In your test project:
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI (`Program.cs`)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

Your `ReportGenerator` would change from calling statics directly to using the injected abstraction:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

namespace NeedsWrappers.Services;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        var content = $"Report: {reportName}\nGenerated: ...";

        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, content);
        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("Report: sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

### Quick mapping cheat-sheet

| Direct static call | `IFileSystem` equivalent |
|---|---|
| `File.ReadAllText(p)` | `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(p)` |
| `File.WriteAllText(p, c)` | `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(p, c)` |
| `Directory.Exists(p)` | `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(p)` |

> **Bonus:** your `ReportGenerator` also uses `DateTime.UtcNow`, `Environment.*`, and `Console.WriteLine`. For `DateTime`, inject the built-in `TimeProvider` (.NET 8+). For `Environment` and `Console`, small custom wrappers work well — want me to generate those too?
